"""
mkt-context | 1samuel | ch 22-24 gap-fill (72 missing verses)
David's outlaw period: Adullam band, Nob massacre, Keilah rescue,
Ziphite betrayal, En Gedi cave encounter with Saul.
Historical/ANE background: Habiru/Apiru parallels, Nob priestly city,
ephod divination, kanaph (hem-cutting), mashiach YHWH theology.
Run: python3 scripts/zc-context-1samuel-22-24-fill.py
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    if p.exists():
        return json.loads(p.read_text())
    return {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

SAMUEL1 = {
  "22": {
    "2": "<p>David's outlaw band at Adullam — 'all who were under pressure, all in debt, all who were bitter' (<em>kol ish matzok, kol ish asher lo nosheh, kol ish mar nefesh</em>) — has exact parallels in the 14th century BCE Amarna Letters, which describe the <em>Hapiru/Apiru</em>: landless, indebted, socially marginal people who gathered under strong leaders in the hill country. The Amarna texts from Canaanite city-state rulers complain to Pharaoh that the <em>Hapiru</em> are raiding their territories under leaders like Lab'ayu of Shechem. The social profile matches David's followers precisely: economic refugees, debtors fleeing creditors, the disaffected. David becomes the focal point for everyone the existing order has failed, a pattern that recurs in Israelite history (Jephthah, Judg 11:3) and anticipates the gathering of the marginalized around Jesus (Matt 9:10-13).</p>",
    "3": "<p>David's request for asylum for his parents from the king of Moab reflects the family connection through Ruth (Ruth 4:17-22). Moab is not merely a foreign kingdom but David's ancestral homeland through his great-grandmother. The act of placing his parents 'in the keeping of' (<em>lifnei melech moav</em>, literally 'before the face of the king of Moab') follows diplomatic asylum protocols: the king's personal protection is sought, not merely refuge in the territory. Mizpeh of Moab is unidentified but was likely a Moabite border fortress. David's family remains there 'all the while David was in the stronghold' — the duration of the outlaw period. The Moabite asylum continues the Ruth-trajectory: foreign kindness to the Davidic line.</p>",
    "4": "<p>The statement that David's parents stayed at Mizpeh 'all the while David was in the stronghold' (<em>kol yemei heyot David bametzudah</em>) indicates the Adullam cave period extended for considerable time. <em>Metzudah</em> (stronghold) refers to natural fortresses in the Judean hill country — the same word used for Masada (<em>metzada</em>). David's mobile refugee community rotated among these natural fortresses in the wilderness, which provided both protection and tactical advantage. The Judean wilderness, with its deep wadis, inaccessible cave systems, and dramatic topography, was historically the refuge of the fugitive, the prophet, and the revolutionary.</p>",
    "5": "<p>Gad the prophet's instruction — 'do not stay in the stronghold; go into the land of Judah' — introduces one of David's court prophets. <em>Gad</em> (fortune/troop) will later be David's 'court seer' (<em>navi</em>, 2 Sam 24:11) who delivers the plague judgment after the census. The prophet as military advisor was standard in the ancient Near East: Mari texts (18th c. BCE) document prophets giving military directives to kings, and the role of <em>ish elohim</em> as strategic counsel appears throughout Samuel-Kings. Gad's instruction to return to Judah rather than remain in the Adullam cave system reflects the theological priority: David must stay connected to his ancestral territory, not become a permanent exile. The prophet channels divine strategy into military decisions.</p>",
    "6": "<p>Saul's court at Gibeah (<em>giv'ah</em>, the hill — modern Tell el-Ful, north of Jerusalem) is depicted here as a paranoid assembly. The king sitting 'under the tamarisk tree (<em>eshel</em>) on the height (<em>bammah</em>) at Gibeah, with his spear in his hand' is a formal military court posture — the king as warrior-judge, holding his spear as the symbol of royal authority (the same spear he threw at David, 18:11). The tamarisk (<em>eshel</em>) was associated with sacred sites (Abraham planted a tamarisk at Beer-sheba, Gen 21:33) and shade for desert assembly. Saul's court has the trappings of legitimacy but has devolved into factional suspicion.</p>",
    "7": "<p>'Will the son of Jesse give every one of you fields and vineyards? Will he make all of you commanders of thousands and hundreds?' — Saul's appeal to his Benjaminite followers exposes his understanding of royal patronage. Land grants and military appointments were the currency of loyalty in ancient Near Eastern kingship. The Amarna period shows Canaanite kings distributing land to loyal retainers; Saul fears David's superior charisma will redirect this patronage network. The appeal to tribal loyalty — 'all you Benjaminites' (<em>benei yemini</em>) — is the explicit tribal-political argument: a Judahite king will not favor Benjamin. Saul's tribal-dynastic calculation was accurate: Solomon's reign would see northern and Benjaminite tensions.</p>",
    "8": "<p>'None of you is sorry for me (<em>chala mi mekem</em>). None of you has disclosed to me that my son has made a covenant with the son of Jesse.' Saul's complaint reveals his isolation — his own son's covenant with David (18:3; 20:16) has been concealed from him. The phrase <em>karet brit</em> (cut a covenant) for the Jonathan-David bond signals its formal, legally-binding character. The covenant represented not merely personal friendship but a political transfer of the succession: Jonathan acknowledges David as the future king and binds himself to serve under him (20:13-17). Saul intuits that the covenant represents a dynastic succession, not merely a personal bond, and he is correct.</p>",
    "10": "<p>Ahimelech's consultation of YHWH on David's behalf is described with the verb <em>sha'al</em> (to inquire), the same technical term used for consulting YHWH through the ephod. The procedure likely involved the <em>urim</em> and <em>thummim</em>, two oracular objects kept in the high priest's breastplate (<em>choshen</em>) and used for binary divine-yes/no inquiries (cf. Num 27:21; Ezra 2:63). Ahimelech also gave David the 'bread of the Presence' (<em>lechem panim</em>, 21:6) and Goliath's sword. These three acts — divination, sacred bread, weapons — constitute the priest's full arsenal of support and will seal his execution.</p>",
    "11": "<p>Saul summoned 'Ahimelech son of Ahitub the priest and all his father's house — all the priests at Nob' (<em>kol bet aviv hakohanim asher benov</em>). Nob was the priestly settlement housing the Elide priesthood displaced from Shiloh after the Philistine capture of the ark (1 Sam 4-5). The city functioned as a sacred precinct with the tabernacle furnishings and the bread of the Presence (cf. 21:1-9). Archaeological surveys suggest Nob was located northeast of Jerusalem on the Mount of Olives ridge, visible from the city. The entire priestly community — multiple families — appears before Saul, exposing all of them to the coming judgment.</p>",
    "12": "<p>'Hear now, son of Ahitub' — Saul addresses Ahimelech by his genealogy: <em>ben-achituv</em> (son of Ahitub). Ahitub was the son of Phinehas, son of Eli (1 Sam 14:3) — placing Ahimelech squarely in the Elide line that Samuel's birth narrative condemned (1 Sam 2:27-36). The prophecy against the house of Eli — 'on one day both of them shall die' (2:34) and 'every one of your descendants who is left will come to beg him for a piece of silver or a loaf of bread' (2:36) — is about to be fulfilled in the Nob massacre. Ahimelech's response 'Here I am, my lord' (<em>hineni adoni</em>) uses the theophanic response formula — the word of a loyal servant answering his lord's summons.</p>",
    "13": "<p>'Why have you conspired against me (<em>qeshartem</em>), you and the son of Jesse, in that you gave him bread and a sword and have inquired of God for him?' Saul's accusation constructs a conspiracy (<em>qesher</em>, binding/plotting) from Ahimelech's acts of priestly hospitality. The word <em>qesher</em> (conspiracy) is the same used for political rebellion against the throne in Kings (1 Kgs 15:27; 16:9 etc.). Saul reframes priestly ministry as treason, a fatal category error: Ahimelech acted according to his priestly office, not political allegiance. The ANE analogy: Assyrian records show kings executing priests who performed divination for rivals — Saul's accusation fits a pattern of royal control of priestly oracular functions.</p>",
    "14": "<p>Ahimelech's defense — 'who among all your servants is so trusted as David, the king's son-in-law (<em>chatan hamelech</em>), captain of your bodyguard (<em>sar el mishma'atecha</em>), and honored in your house (<em>nikbad beitecha</em>)?' — presents David's royal credentials. Three titles: son-in-law of the king (the Michal marriage), commander of the royal guard (the position given after Goliath), and honoree of the household. From Ahimelech's perspective, assisting the king's most trusted officer was normal priestly conduct, not treason. The defense is legally impeccable and morally correct — and will make no difference to Saul's execution order.</p>",
    "15": "<p>'Was it the first time I inquired of God for him? Far be it from me! Let not the king impute anything to his servant or to all the house of my father, for your servant knew nothing (<em>lo yada et kol-zot avdecha qaton vegadol</em>) of all this.' Ahimelech denies knowledge of any conspiracy, claiming this is not the first time he has provided divination services for David — implying that divination for the king's officers was routine priestly practice. The phrase 'far be it from me' (<em>chalilah li</em>) is the strongest expression of horrified repudiation. His final appeal — 'let not the king impute this to his servant' (<em>al-yashim adoni baavdo davar</em>) — is the language of royal pardon. It is refused.</p>",
    "16": "<p>'You shall surely die (<em>mot tamut</em>), Ahimelech, you and all your father's house (<em>kol beit avicha</em>).' The death sentence uses the infinitive absolute <em>mot tamut</em> for emphasis — the strongest form of the death penalty declaration. Extending the sentence to 'all your father's house' enacts the principle of collective family guilt that Israelite law actually prohibited (Deut 24:16 — 'fathers shall not be put to death for their children, nor children for their fathers; each shall be put to death for his own sin'). Saul violates his own law's prohibition on collective punishment. The massacre of Nob (85 priests plus the entire city, v18-19) is one of the most extreme acts of royal terror in the entire DH narrative of the monarchy.</p>",
    "17": "<p>'Turn and kill the priests of YHWH (<em>sovu uphge'u vekohanei YHWH</em>).' The officers of Saul's guard refuse: 'they would not put out their hand to fall upon the priests of YHWH' (<em>ki lo avu lishloach yad lifgo'a vekohanei YHWH</em>). The guards' refusal is remarkable: in the ancient world, soldiers obeyed royal kill-orders. The refusal signals that the Israelite soldiers recognized the priestly office as inviolable — attacking priests of YHWH would be sacrilege even by royal command. This is the precise moment when Saul's kingship crosses a line his own soldiers will not follow. The willingness-gap between Saul and his troops mirrors the withdrawal of YHWH's spirit and Samuel's anointing of David as the real king.</p>",
    "18": "<p>Doeg the Edomite's execution of the 85 priests — <em>vayipag hu bekohanim vayyamet bayom hahu shemonim vachamishah ish noshe efod bad</em> — fulfills the prophecy against Eli's house (2:31-33). The number 85 is specific and large: this is the comprehensive destruction of the Nob priestly community. Doeg is an Edomite, a non-Israelite, which explains his willingness to strike where Israelite soldiers refused. ANE parallel: foreign mercenaries and bodyguards were routinely used by ancient Near Eastern kings for executions that their own nationals would not perform — Uriah the Hittite in David's service, Carian and Cherethite mercenaries, Assyrian <em>shaltu</em> officers. The use of a foreigner to kill Israel's priests signals the depth of Saul's alienation from the covenant order.</p>",
    "19": "<p>The total destruction of Nob — 'men and women, children and infants, cattle, donkeys, and sheep' (<em>uvet-anashim venashim velaf vetzeun uvequr lefi-charev</em>) — follows the vocabulary of <em>cherem</em> (the ban of total destruction). The same formula was used for Jericho (Josh 6:21) and other cities devoted to YHWH for destruction. The devastating irony is that Saul, who refused to apply the <em>cherem</em> to Amalek as YHWH commanded (ch15), readily applies it to an Israelite priestly city without divine authorization. His disobedience in the sacred war against Amalek is mirrored in his unauthorized <em>cherem</em> against Nob: he withholds judgment where commanded and applies it where forbidden.</p>",
    "21": "<p>Abiathar's survival and escape to David fulfills YHWH's guarantee to the house of Eli: 'I will raise up for myself a faithful priest' (2:35). The 'man before my anointed forever' in that prophecy is linked to the Zadokite line, but the immediate fulfillment is Abiathar's survival. Abiathar becomes David's high priest throughout his reign, and the ephod he carries (v20) becomes the oracular apparatus through which David inquires of YHWH (23:9-12; 30:7-8). The survival of one priest — exactly one — from the entire Nob massacre, with the ephod, is the mechanism by which divine guidance continues to reach David.</p>",
    "22": "<p>'I knew on that day (<em>yadati bayom hahu</em>), when Doeg the Edomite was there, that he would surely tell Saul.' David acknowledges complicity: his presence at Nob and his knowledge of Doeg's presence made him an indirect cause of the massacre. This confession of moral responsibility is historically accurate to ANE accountability culture: the king who benefits from an action bears responsibility for it even if he did not order it. David's accountability here parallels later situations (Uriah) where his actions set chains of consequences in motion. The admission 'I have occasioned the death of all the persons of your father's house' (<em>anochi savoti bekol nefesh beit avicha</em>) uses <em>savav</em> (to turn/surround) — I have caused to turn upon.</p>",
    "23": "<p>'Stay with me; do not be afraid. For the one who seeks my life seeks your life (<em>ki asher yevaqesh et nafshi yevaqesh et nafshecha</em>). For you are safe with me (<em>mishmereth ata imadi</em>).' David's invitation to Abiathar uses covenant security language: <em>mishmereth</em> (guard, custody, safekeeping) — you are under my protection. The mutual danger establishes a mutual protection covenant: Saul's pursuit of David covers Abiathar too. This covenant of protection creates the relationship that sustains the David-Abiathar alliance throughout the outlaw period and the reigns of David. Abiathar's eventual expulsion by Solomon (1 Kgs 2:26-27) fulfills the Eli-house prophecy's final clause.</p>"
  },
  "23": {
    "2": "<p>'David inquired of YHWH (<em>vayyish'al david beYHWH</em>): Should I go and attack these Philistines?' The first ephod consultation of ch23. The verb <em>sha'al beYHWH</em> (to ask/inquire of YHWH) is the technical term for oracular consultation through the priestly apparatus — specifically the urim and thummim. The binary nature of the response ('go and attack') fits the urim/thummim format: the priest presents a yes/no question and receives a divinely determined lot answer. David's practice of consistently consulting YHWH before military action is the defining contrast with Saul, who consulted the witch of Endor when the legitimate oracular apparatus was unavailable (ch28). The responsiveness of YHWH to David's inquiries — vs. YHWH's silence to Saul — is one of the DH's key indicators of covenantal standing.</p>",
    "3": "<p>The soldiers' reluctance — 'here in Judah we are afraid; how much more if we go to Keilah against the armies of the Philistines?' — reflects the military reality of David's band. His men are refugees, debtors, and the socially marginal (22:2), not professional soldiers. Their doubt is strategically reasonable: Keilah is a fortified city in the Shephelah, closer to Philistine territory, and defending it against a Philistine raiding force means fighting in the open lowland terrain that favored Philistine chariot-heavy forces. The men's military assessment is competent; their faith is deficient. David's second inquiry (v4) is prompted by their legitimate concern, and the doubled divine assurance functions as an oracle of divine reinforcement.</p>",
    "4": "<p>David 'inquired of YHWH again' (<em>vayoseph david lish'ol beYHWH od</em>) — the double consultation is a unique feature of 1 Samuel's ephod-divination narrative. The first inquiry (v2) received a positive answer; the second (v4) receives both a positive answer and a specific promise: 'I am giving the Philistines into your hand' (<em>ki noten anokhi et-haplishtim beyadecha</em>). The repeated consultation follows a principle visible throughout ANE oracular practice: significant military decisions warranted multiple confirmations (cf. the double-dream interpretation in Gen 41:32 — 'because the thing has been established by God'). The double divine confirmation overrides the soldiers' doubt.</p>",
    "5": "<p>The Keilah victory demonstrates David's military capacity while simultaneously creating a political liability: he has saved a Judahite city from Philistine raiding, which should earn him loyalty, but instead makes him vulnerable — Saul knows exactly where he is. The rescue of Keilah is a microcosm of David's entire pre-kingship period: faithful covenant action (protecting Israel from Philistines) leads not to reward but to increased danger. The liberation of Keilah also establishes the pattern of David as protector of the settled population that will later justify his kingship over all Israel.</p>",
    "6": "<p>Abiathar's ephod is introduced as the oracular instrument available to David: 'when Abiathar son of Ahimelech fled to David at Keilah, he came down with an ephod in his hand' (<em>ephod yarad beyado</em>). The ephod (<em>efod</em>) here is the priestly garment containing the breastplate with the urim and thummim (Exod 28:6-30), not the simple linen ephod of 2:18. This ephod is the portable oracular apparatus that makes the field-campaigns of the outlaw period strategically and theologically coherent: David can inquire of YHWH wherever he goes. The mobility of the ephod reflects the pre-temple period when divine presence was not yet fixed in Jerusalem — the ark, the ephod, and the tabernacle all moved with the community.</p>",
    "7": "<p>Saul's intelligence report — 'God has given him into my hand, for he has imprisoned himself by entering a town with gates and bars' (<em>niskbar ki ba el-ir daltayim uverichim</em>) — misreads the situation. Saul interprets David's presence in a walled city as a tactical trap; actually David holds the oracular means of escape. The phrase <em>niskbar</em> (he has trapped/imprisoned himself) uses the root <em>s-k-r</em> (to shut/close), referring to the locked gates. Saul's geography is correct but his theology is inverted: he thinks the walls work against David, but the walls work against Saul too — he cannot take the city by siege quickly. Saul's repeated misreading of providential situations is a DH theme.</p>",
    "8": "<p>Saul 'summoned all the people to war' (<em>vayitz'aq saul et-kol-ha'am lemilchamah lalechet keilah</em>) — mobilizing the full levy for what amounts to a pursuit of one fugitive. This disproportionate military response reflects the depth of Saul's obsession and the degree to which the pursuit of David had displaced normal royal priorities. ANE analogy: the Mari archives document kings mobilizing full tribal levies for pursuits of rebellious vassals and bandits, but the scale was usually limited to the target's actual military threat. Saul's mobilization of 'all the people' against David's 600-man band is a sign of political dysfunction — the king is spending state resources on a personal vendetta.</p>",
    "9": "<p>'David learned that Saul was plotting evil against him' — the intelligence apparatus of David's band includes informers and scouts who track Saul's movements. <em>Chorash alav ra'ah</em> (plotting evil against him) uses the word <em>churash</em> (to plow/devise, also to be silent), suggesting Saul's plotting was covert. David's response is to 'bring the ephod here' (<em>hagisha ha-efod</em>) — the technical command to the priest to prepare the oracular apparatus. The oracular inquiry is the immediate response to the intelligence threat: before tactical planning, divine consultation. This is the ANE model of warfare-theology: military commanders consulted oracular institutions before campaigns (Assyrian king's <em>tamitu</em> queries to Shamash; Hittite oracular inquiries before battle).</p>",
    "10": "<p>David's consultation formula — 'YHWH, God of Israel, your servant has heard that Saul is seeking to come to Keilah to destroy the city on my account (<em>bishvili</em>)' — frames the oracular question with full disclosure of the situation. The prayer-question format before the urim/thummim consultation identifies the specific scenario being submitted for divine adjudication. This transparency before YHWH contrasts with Saul's increasingly secret plotting; David's oracular life is public and transparent, laid before YHWH precisely because he trusts the answer. The word <em>bishvili</em> (on my account) shows David's moral seriousness: he is asking whether his presence is putting Keilah at risk.</p>",
    "11": "<p>The double question — 'will the lords of Keilah surrender me to him? Will Saul come down as your servant has heard?' (<em>ha-yisgeruni ba'alei qeilah beyado hayerd saul ka-asher shama avdecha</em>) — elicits two divine answers both in the affirmative. The Keilahites would surrender David; Saul would indeed come. The double question-and-answer format is unique in biblical oracular narrative: normally the urim/thummim gives a single yes/no response to a single question. The double inquiry may represent two separate lot-throws, or a more complex procedure. The crucial information is that the people David just rescued will betray him to save their city — a detail that resonates with Jesus's own experience of crowds that received miracles and then turned against him.</p>",
    "12": "<p>'Will the people of Keilah surrender me and my men to Saul?' — the decisive question. YHWH's answer: 'They will surrender you.' (<em>yisageru</em>, they will deliver up/shut/hand over). The verb <em>sagar</em> (to shut/deliver up) is the same word used for extradition in international treaties — the Keilahites would deliver David as a political prisoner to the king. The city gate context of ancient treaty language makes this response profoundly political: Keilah would fulfill state obligation to the crown by surrendering a fugitive, overriding the moral obligation to the person who saved them. David's escape from Keilah before Saul arrives represents the oracular system working perfectly: foreknowledge enables avoidance.</p>",
    "13": "<p>David departed with 'about six hundred men' (<em>keshesh me'ot ish</em>) — the number has grown from the 400 at Adullam (22:2). The growth of David's following during the outlaw period is historically analogous to the growth of rebel or proto-monarchical bands in other ANE contexts: the Mari documents show how Yamina tribal bands swelled around charismatic leaders; the LBA 'outlaw' groups (Hapiru) grew through accretion of the dispossessed. David's band is becoming an army, and the increasing numbers reflect the population's implicit evaluation of who the real king is.</p>",
    "14": "<p>David lived in the wilderness strongholds (<em>metzudot bamidbar</em>) and in the hill country of the wilderness of Ziph. The Judean wilderness was a wilderness of options: its topography — steep chalk ridges, deep wadis, cave systems, sparse vegetation — made it defensible but uninhabitable for large forces. Roman-era accounts and Qumran archaeology confirm the wilderness's hospitality to fugitive communities. 'Saul sought him every day but God did not give him into his hand' (<em>velo netano elohim beyado</em>) — the DH narrator's theological summary. The entire wilderness pursuit is framed as divine protection: every near-miss is YHWH's intervention.</p>",
    "15": "<p>'David saw that Saul had come out to seek his life' — the vocabulary of pursuit (<em>levaqesh et nafshecha</em>, to seek your life) frames Saul's activity as a murder-hunt rather than a law-enforcement action. David 'was in the wilderness of Ziph at Horesh' — <em>choresshah</em> (thicket/wooded area), a place name from the root <em>churesh</em> (forest/wood), appropriate to the vegetation of the chalk ridges above the Dead Sea. The Wilderness of Ziph is identified with the area around Tell Zif south of Hebron.</p>",
    "16": "<p>Jonathan's final visit to David 'at Horesh' (<em>vayaqam yehonatan ben-shaul vayelech el-david chorshah</em>) is the last recorded meeting of the two covenant partners. <em>Vayaqem</em> (he arose and went) — the initiative is Jonathan's; he seeks out the fugitive. 'He strengthened his hand in God' (<em>vayechazzeq et-yado baelohim</em>) — <em>chizzaq</em> (to strengthen, fortify) is the word of military encouragement (Josh 1:6-9 'be strong and courageous'); Jonathan gives David the same fortification that YHWH gave Joshua before the conquest. The human act (Jonathan's encouragement) mediates the divine strength — the covenant friend is a conduit of divine empowerment.</p>",
    "17": "<p>'Do not be afraid, for Saul my father shall not find you (<em>lo timtza'echa yad avi saul</em>). You shall be king over Israel (<em>umalkta al-yisrael</em>), and I shall be second to you (<em>va'ani ehyeh-lecha lemishneh</em>).' Jonathan's prophetic affirmation — 'you shall be king' — spoken during David's darkest period, when he is hiding in the Judean wilderness with no army and no territory, is a remarkable act of faith and political courage. <em>Mishneh</em> (second-in-command) was the standard term for the crown prince's designated deputy — Jonathan is voluntarily surrendering his own claim to the succession and accepting the role of David's principal minister. This voluntary abnegation of dynastic right is unique in ANE succession narratives: normally the crown prince fought for his position.</p>",
    "19": "<p>The Ziphites come to Saul at Gibeah to betray David's location: 'Is David not hiding among us in the strongholds at Horesh?' — Saul had sent runners throughout Judah looking for David (22:7-8), and the Ziphites respond to the political opportunity. The Ziphites' territory (Tell Zif area) was where David was hiding — their denunciation was local knowledge shared for political benefit. In the ancient world, harboring a fugitive from the king was politically dangerous; the Ziphites' betrayal is rational political self-preservation. Their repeated betrayals (v19-24; 26:1) show that David's refuge in his own tribal territory was precarious — even Judahites were not uniformly loyal to their future king.</p>",
    "20": "<p>'Now, O king, come down whenever your soul desires, and our part shall be to surrender him to the king's hand' (<em>ve'alenu lesagro beyad hamelech</em>). The Ziphites offer to perform the <em>sagar</em> (surrender/extradition) action that the Keilahites had also been expected to perform (v12). The formal extradition language mirrors inter-city treaty obligations: 'your soul desires' (<em>le-kol awat nafshecha</em>) is the treaty formula of servile deference. The Ziphite offer creates the closest Saul comes to catching David — a circumstance from which only a providential Philistine raid saves him (v27-28).</p>",
    "21": "<p>'Blessed are you by YHWH (<em>beruchim atem laYHWH</em>), for you have had compassion on me' — Saul blesses the Ziphites in YHWH's name for their betrayal. The theological grotesquerie is intentional: a king whose covenantal standing has been withdrawn invokes the covenant God to bless informers who will help him murder the covenant God's anointed. The irony is DH-characteristic: Saul uses religious language mechanically, without the substance of relationship that gives it meaning. His blessing of the Ziphites for compassing David's death is the inverse of YHWH's protection of David — two competing claims of divine sanction.</p>",
    "22": "<p>'Prepare further. Make sure of the place where his foot is (<em>da'u na ure'u et-hamaqom asher tihyeh raglo</em>), and who has seen him there.' Intelligence-gathering procedure: Saul asks for surveillance of David's exact movements. <em>Maqom</em> (place) and <em>raglo</em> (his foot) suggest continuous tracking of footprints and campsites in the wilderness terrain. The specific intelligence request — who has seen him there — indicates Saul is running a network of informers in the Judean wilderness. This intelligence apparatus mirrors the counter-intelligence that David himself runs (he knows Saul is plotting before Saul can execute, v9).</p>",
    "23": "<p>'Return to me with reliable information (<em>vahashivtem elai davar nachon</em>), and I will go with you.' <em>Nachon</em> (confirmed, reliable, certain) is the same word used for divine oracles that are 'established/sure' — Saul applies prophetic certainty-language to his spy reports. The instruction to 'survey all the hiding places where he hides (<em>kol-hamecharvaot asher yitchabbe sham</em>)' shows knowledge of David's guerrilla tactics: the use of caves and rock formations as sequential temporary bases. The Judean wilderness has hundreds of such sites, making comprehensive surveillance nearly impossible without local guides.</p>",
    "24": "<p>David and his men were in the 'wilderness of Maon' (<em>midbar ma'on</em>) in the Arabah south of Jeshimon — a barren, rocky plateau south of Hebron in the Judean desert approaching the Dead Sea. The geography is precisely described: 'Saul and his men went on one side of the mountain (<em>mippo hazeh</em>), and David and his men were on the other side of the mountain' — a tactical standoff on opposite slopes of the same massif, with David encircled but not yet captured. The mountain that separates them is a physical expression of the providential protection of the wilderness itself.</p>",
    "25": "<p>Saul's pursuit — 'the rock' (<em>hasela</em>) in the wilderness of Maon — may be the site later called Sela-hammahlekoth (v28, 'rock of division/escape'). The narrative is building to a geographical-providential climax: David is about to be cornered when the Philistine raid intervenes. The topography serves the theology: the wilderness itself protects the fugitive. This pattern recurs in Israelite literature — the wilderness as the place where YHWH's protection is most direct, unmediated by human institutions.</p>",
    "26": "<p>The pursuit narrows to its closest approach: 'Saul and his men were closing in on David and his men to capture them' (<em>vayehi saul uminashehu miqqetsath hahar mizeh vedavid uminashehu miqqetzat hahar mizeh</em>) — both parties moving along ridges of the same massif. The syntax mirrors the geography: the two parties described in parallel clauses, converging. The word <em>nahash</em> (to pursue quickly) suggests urgency; David's capture is at the point of inevitable completion.</p>",
    "27": "<p>The Philistine raid that saves David — 'a messenger came to Saul: &ldquo;Come quickly, for the Philistines have raided the land&rdquo;' (<em>chush ulechu ki pashetu hafilistim al-ha'aretz</em>) — is the classic DH pattern of providential rescue through historical contingency. The Philistine raid is not miraculous in mechanism (it is a normal military event) but miraculous in timing. ANE historiography consistently read the providential significance of coincidental timing: an event that breaks a crisis at the exact moment of maximum danger was attributed to divine intervention regardless of natural cause. The Philistines' raid functions as YHWH's military intervention on David's behalf.</p>",
    "28": "<p>The place was named Sela-hammahlekoth (<em>sela hamachlekot</em>, rock of divisions/separations) — a name that commemorates the providential divide. <em>Machaleket</em> (portion/division, from <em>chalaq</em>, to divide/share) may mean the rock of the escape, where the pursuers and the pursued were divided. The naming of places after providential events is common in the DH (Beer of Lahairoi, Gen 16:14; Massah and Meribah, Exod 17:7) — topography is made to carry theological memory. Every traveler who passed Sela-hammahlekoth afterward would ask and be told the story of YHWH's protection of the anointed king.</p>",
    "29": "<p>David went up from there and lived in the strongholds of En Gedi — <em>atzade ein gedi</em> (the rocky fortresses of Ein Gedi). Ein Gedi (modern Ein Gedi, on the western shore of the Dead Sea) is one of the most dramatic locations in the Judean wilderness: a natural oasis formed by several fresh-water springs in the middle of the Dead Sea shoreline, surrounded by vertiginous chalk cliffs with numerous cave systems. The name means 'spring of the kid/young goat' (<em>ein</em> = spring, <em>gedi</em> = kid). The terrain was ideal for a guerrilla force: inaccessible to conventional armies, providing water, and offering commanding views of any approach. The David-at-En-Gedi tradition formed the background for Psalm 57 and Psalm 142 (both headed 'when he was in the cave').</p>"
  },
  "24": {
    "1": "<p>Saul returned from pursuing the Philistines (the same campaign that was diverted from David at 23:27-28) and was told: 'David is in the wilderness of En Gedi' (<em>david bemidbar ein gedi</em>). The information flows back to Saul immediately after the Philistine campaign — his intelligence network monitors David continuously. En Gedi's location on the Dead Sea shore made it appear to be an isolated pocket: sea to the east, sheer cliffs to the west, narrow approach from north and south. Saul could calculate that David was boxed in without the open terrain for escape that the Judean hill country offered. The apparent geographical trap sets the scene for a providential reversal.</p>",
    "2": "<p>'Saul took three thousand chosen men from all Israel' (<em>vayiqqach saul shloshet alfei ish berurei yisrael</em>) to the Rocks of the Wild Goats at En Gedi. Three thousand is a substantial standing force — the same number as Saul's original standing army (13:2). The 'rocks of the wild goats' (<em>tzurei ha-ye'elim</em>) refers to the ibex habitat of the En Gedi cliffs — a toponym that captures the terrain precisely: <em>ya'el</em> (ibex/mountain goat) is well-attested in the Ein Gedi area from antiquity to the present. The specificity of the geographical reference suggests the narrative draws on authentic location memory for the En Gedi cave episodes.</p>",
    "5": "<p>David's heart struck him after cutting the corner of Saul's robe — <em>vayach lev-david oto</em> (his heart struck him, i.e., conscience smote him). The phrase is unique in the OT — elsewhere the heart 'falls' or 'fears,' but 'striking the heart' describes an inner moral alarm. The reason: the hem/corner of the robe (<em>kanaph</em>) carried legal-covenantal significance. In ANE legal practice (attested in Mesopotamian documents), cutting a person's garment hem was equivalent to canceling their identity or claim — used in divorce proceedings and social degradation ceremonies. Even this symbolic diminishment of the king's honor was too much for David's theological conscience regarding the anointed (<em>mashiach</em>).</p>",
    "6": "<p>'The LORD forbid that I should do this thing to my lord, the LORD's anointed (<em>limeshiach YHWH</em>), to put out my hand against him' — David's theological restraint is grounded in the concept of the <em>mashiach YHWH</em> (YHWH's anointed). The anointed king was consecrated by the same oil used for priests and tabernacle objects (Exod 29:7; 30:22-33) — touching an anointed was like touching a sacred vessel. The inviolability of the anointed is a legal-theological principle that David articulates more fully than any other character in Samuel: even a bad king, chosen by YHWH and anointed by his prophet, possesses a sacredness that no human hands should violate. David's forbearance of Saul establishes the principle that determines his own future protection.</p>",
    "7": "<p>'With these words David held his men back (<em>vayeshassa david et-anashav badevarim</em>) and did not allow them to attack Saul.' The verb <em>shissa</em> (to split/cleave, hence to restrain/hold back) is unusual — it suggests David had to actively break apart his men's momentum toward action. The men's eagerness to kill Saul (v4's quotation: 'here is the day YHWH told you about — I will give your enemy into your hands') represents a genuine theological position: YHWH had given David this opportunity, so killing Saul must be the divine intention. David's counter-theology — that YHWH's gift of opportunity does not automatically mean YHWH's command to act — is a sophisticated reading of divine providence that his men lacked.</p>",
    "8": "<p>'Afterward David also arose (<em>vayaqam acharei ken david</em>) and went out of the cave and called after Saul' — David's public confrontation follows only after Saul has exited the cave. He does not ambush from inside; he emerges and speaks openly. <em>Vayiqra acharei shaul</em> (he called after Saul) — the word <em>qara</em> (to call out, proclaim) suggests a public declaration, not a private conversation. David's speech (vv9-15) is carefully structured as a legal plea before the king, the ten witnesses of vv2, and YHWH as judge. The speech is a formal legal disputation (<em>riv</em>) before divine judgment.</p>",
    "9": "<p>'Why do you listen to the words of men who say, &ldquo;David seeks your harm?&rdquo;' — David identifies the misinformation mechanism: informers have constructed the conspiracy narrative that drives Saul's pursuit. The word <em>shome'a</em> (listening, giving ear to) is the first charge in the speech: Saul has believed accusers over the evidence. The legal genre of the disputation speech requires first identifying the false accusation, then presenting counter-evidence. David's counter-evidence is the robe-corner itself: the material artifact that disproves the accusation of murderous intent.</p>",
    "10": "<p>'This day your eyes have seen how YHWH has given you into my hand in the cave (<em>hinneh ra'u einecha hayom et asher natacha YHWH beyadi hamearah</em>). Some urged me to kill you, but I spared you.' The phrase <em>natacha YHWH beyadi</em> (YHWH gave you into my hand) uses the standard language of holy-war victory — the same formula used when YHWH delivered enemies to Israel's armies. David acknowledges the theological framing his men used (YHWH gave you into my hand) but draws the opposite conclusion: YHWH's provision of opportunity does not require human action to complete it. He says 'I spared you' (<em>vatachos alecha eini</em>, my eye had compassion on you) — the same compassion Saul refused to show Agag (ch15). The reversal is pointed.</p>",
    "11": "<p>'See, my father (<em>re'eh avi</em>), see the corner of your robe in my hand' — <em>avi</em> (my father) is a form of respectful address to a superior; here it may carry additional weight of the son-in-law relationship (David is married to Saul's daughter Michal). The robe-corner as exhibit A: the material evidence of David's restraint. The cutting of the robe corner without harming the person is the demonstration that 'I have not sinned against you (<em>lo chatati lach</em>), though you hunt my life (<em>letzqod et nafshi</em>).' The legal-courtroom structure of the speech is most visible here: evidence is presented, the charge of treason is rebutted by the evidence.</p>",
    "12": "<p>'May YHWH judge between me and you (<em>yishpot YHWH beini uvenecha</em>), and may YHWH avenge me upon you (<em>uneqamani YHWH mimecha</em>). But my hand will not be against you.' David submits the dispute to divine judgment — the standard ANE procedure when human courts cannot adjudicate (cf. Jephthah's speech to the Ammonites, Judg 11:27: 'let YHWH the Judge decide today between the sons of Israel and the sons of Ammon'). The refusal of personal vengeance combined with the appeal to divine judgment is not passive fatalism but active covenantal faith: YHWH's court is the final appeals court, and David files his claim there.</p>",
    "13": "<p>'As the ancient proverb says, &ldquo;From evildoers comes evil&rdquo; (<em>meresha'im yetzeh resha</em>)' — David cites a proverbial wisdom tradition to make his point: actions reveal character. Since his hand has not acted against Saul despite the opportunity, his character is not that of a wicked person. The appeal to proverbial wisdom (<em>mashal qadmonim</em>, proverb of the ancient ones) is a rhetorical move that grounds the argument in recognized communal wisdom rather than David's own self-assessment. ANE wisdom literature (Egyptian Instruction texts, Mesopotamian proverb collections) was widely circulated and cited in legal contexts — a proverb's authority transcended the speaker's personal interest.</p>",
    "15": "<p>'After whom do you pursue, O king of Israel? After whom do you chase? After a dead dog (<em>acharei kelev met</em>)? After a single flea (<em>acharei parosh echad</em>)?' David's self-deprecation employs the standard rhetoric of ANE petitionary speech: extreme self-diminishment before a superior to elicit compassion. 'Dead dog' and 'flea' represent the opposite extremes of uselessness — one dead and worthless, one so small as to be beneath notice. The rhetorical question underscores the disproportion of the royal pursuit: three thousand men mobilized against one fugitive who poses no actual military threat. The social logic is asymmetry — the mighty hunting the insignificant — which should shame the pursuer.</p>",
    "16": "<p>'May YHWH therefore be judge (<em>hayah YHWH ledayan</em>) and give sentence between me and you, and see and plead my cause (<em>yariv et rivi</em>) and deliver me from your hand.' The vocabulary is entirely legal: <em>dayan</em> (judge), <em>yariv</em> (plead the cause, defend the case), <em>yishpeteni</em> (judge/vindicate me). David is not merely praying but formally filing his legal claim with YHWH as the court of highest jurisdiction. <em>Riv</em> (lawsuit/legal case/contention) is the prophetic lawsuit genre used by Hosea 4:1, Micah 6:1-2, Isaiah 3:13 — YHWH as the plaintiff bringing a case against Israel. Here David inverts the genre: he is the plaintiff, Saul is the defendant, YHWH is the judge.</p>",
    "17": "<p>'Is this your voice, my son David (<em>habincha zeh davidi</em>)?' — Saul's recognition of David's voice after David's speech is the first moment of genuine emotion in the pursuit narrative. <em>Habincha zeh</em> (is this your voice, my son?) — the parental address my son (<em>beni</em>) to David, his former son-in-law and his own son's covenant partner. The question is both recognitional and emotional: Saul hears the voice he knows and asks if he is really hearing it, as if the situation is unbelievable. 'And Saul lifted up his voice and wept' (<em>vayissa saul qolo vayelach</em>). The weeping is genuine: even the most complex tyrant in the Samuel narrative has moments of authentic grief over what he is doing and what he has lost.</p>",
    "18": "<p>'You are more righteous than I (<em>tzaddiq attah mimeni</em>), for you have repaid me good, whereas I have repaid you evil (<em>vaani gamalti lecha ra'ah</em>).' Saul's confession is a formal acknowledgment of guilt in the legal disputation genre: the defendant admits the plaintiff's case. <em>Tzaddiq</em> (righteous, vindicated, innocent) and its opposite <em>rasha</em> (guilty, wicked) are the verdict-words of biblical jurisprudence. Saul's statement is not merely moral but legal: he acknowledges David's innocence and his own guilt. The confession is complete and unreserved — the most honest speech Saul makes in the entire book. Yet it changes nothing: the pursuit will resume (26:2).</p>",
    "19": "<p>'When YHWH delivers your enemy into your hand, who spares him (<em>mi yeshalechemu tov veshalcho lederech tov</em>)?' — Saul endorses David's theological position: restraint toward an enemy whom YHWH has delivered is rare virtue (<em>tov</em>, good/goodness). The acknowledgment that David's restraint is theologically correct is significant: Saul, the king who failed to apply <em>cherem</em> to Amalek, recognizes in David's refusal to kill him the exact kind of principled restraint that he himself lacked. Saul confesses David's righteousness using the same theological framework he violated with Agag. The character contrast is complete.</p>",
    "20": "<p>'And now, behold, I know that you shall surely be king (<em>ki maloch timloch</em>), and that the kingdom of Israel shall be established in your hand (<em>veqama beyad'cha mamlekhet yisrael</em>).' Saul's recognition of David's future kingship — spoken aloud, before witnesses — is the formal concession that completes the chapter's legal disputation. The double infinitive absolute <em>maloch timloch</em> (you will surely reign) mirrors the death sentence formula <em>mot tamut</em> (you will surely die) — the same certainty applied to dynastic succession. Saul is forecasting his own dynasty's end and his rival's rise, which he knows but cannot stop.</p>",
    "21": "<p>'Swear to me therefore by YHWH (<em>hishava li beYHWH</em>) that you will not cut off my descendants after me (<em>im-tachrit et zar'i acharai</em>), and that you will not destroy my name from my father's house' (<em>ushmi mibeit avi</em>). Saul's request reflects the ANE dynastic covenant: a defeated king's last act is to secure dynastic survival for his children. The promise he seeks — protecting descendants and preserving the family name — mirrors the <em>goel</em> obligation in Ruth and the <em>hesed</em> covenant language. David will honor this oath through his treatment of Mephibosheth (2 Sam 9). The covenant with Saul's house is made in YHWH's name and becomes a binding obligation on David's dynasty.</p>",
    "22": "<p>David swore to Saul (<em>vayishava david leshau</em>), and Saul went home while David and his men 'went up to the stronghold' (<em>vayaalah davide uminashehu hametzudah</em>). The narrative ends in geographic separation: Saul to Gibeah, David to the wilderness strongholds. The covenant has been made and the oath sworn, but the circumstances have not fundamentally changed — the same political pressures that drove Saul to pursue David remain. The En Gedi encounter and its covenant are a moment of clarity in the middle of a long storm, not its resolution. The theological point is preserved: David has established the principle of non-violence toward the anointed, which will govern his conduct through the end of Saul's reign.</p>"
  }
}

def main():
    existing = load_comm('mkt-context', '1samuel')
    merge_comm(existing, SAMUEL1)
    save_comm('mkt-context', '1samuel', existing)
    added = sum(len(vv) for vv in SAMUEL1.values())
    print(f'1samuel mkt-context: added up to {added} verses across ch22-24')

if __name__ == '__main__':
    main()
